Message.Title: New highs - Tag along with an exit strategy
Message.Msg: First time above $900 ($915 to be precise) and the volumes were double the averages. The I/O conference was perhaps an excuse, and the fact that nothing big came out of it, may not do much damage immediately. The momentum is only getting stronger, and the new highs are getting further away from the averages. Resistances are not known and supports may have been tested already. So it may be best to join the party and stop predicting the correction. However, keeping stop losses below support points (depending upon your risk appetite) is strongly recommended. Remember, when Apple hit its high, no one thought it will make its low within that year. Google is fighting lawsuits with governments, private companies, associations and what not. The patent infringement lawsuits are on the rise with companies like MGT Capital Investments (MGT) seeking their pound of flesh from casino gaming companies in multi-billion dollar lawsuits. Google itself is fighting several such lawsuits. Launch of Glass will only add to the euphoria, and the recent I/O conference announcements indicate that the improvements may make people spend more time on Google. It will come to know more about us, and make us pay for using its services through the ads. The basic business model is fantastic, but the stock valuations are based more on future successes rather than cynicism of its future innovations. There are social media companies trading at atrocious valuations, and still making good progress. Still, it is better to remain careful and keep an exit point in mind whenever things decisively change for Google stock. It may be a small correction or a deep one, it may be next week or next month or whenever. Best not stick around with hope when that happens (remember Apple). About the highs, it is anybody's guess where it will start to get tired. $950 / $1000 maybe, but no one can be sure. These are technically untested waters.

Topic.Title: Hey Girls..

Message.Msg: PS Kathy. I meant no offense. Kathy, I didn't mean any offense on the GOOG message board. I got burned many times by OTC stocks. After that, I learned to check out 10Q filings. That's where I could find out (under "consolidated and/or consolidated balance" in the links) whether or not company's had been profitable, how long ago, etc. etc. It's just that a lot of OTC companies are perennial money losers. Diluting (adding more shares all the time) so the price never really has a chance to rise). When I didn't have a lot of money to invest, and after getting burned by OTC stocks, I started putting $200 together and buying a few shares in companies that were consistently profitable, barring unforeseen economic turmoil or downturns in their sectors (like F in automotive). I found over time that spending the $7 commission to buy $200 of stock at a time in good companies led to growth over time. Google is my most expensive stock. Most of the others range from $14 to the next highest, BRK/B at $60 when I bought it last year. Now $112. Anyway, I didn't mean to insult you. I'm not a wealthy guy. Just saving for retirement is all. Self employed. $200 here and there can add up over the years. Diversify. First $200 in say, Ford. Next $200 in a tech stock like AMAT, and so on. Lots of eggs in one basket. Then, I added to positions over time until I have a pretty nice looking portfolio where no one stock can crush me. Have a good day, Kathy Danny :-)
